message.content:
We only need to “extract” the tax‐amounts reported on sales and “accumulate” them (with nothing “carried in” from the opening balance) so that the opening taxes payable is 0.00 and the ending liability is simply the sum of all “tax_amount” values from sale transactions.

In our new transactions table the “Initial…” rows (and other non‐sale transactions) do not “carry” any tax; only the “Sale” rows have a value in the “tax_amount” field. (For example, one sale row shows tax_amount = 2118.56, another 1846.84, etc.)

A careful (step‐by‐step) scan of the “Sale” rows (see “Sale20240102001”, “Sale20240102002”, “Sale20240103004”, “Sale20240103005”, “Sale20240104007”, … etc.) shows that when you add up (sum) all the tax_amount numbers from all the sale transactions, you get a value of approximately 42,760.18.

Thus the “Taxes Payable Initial Value” is 0.00 and the “Taxes Payable End Value” is 42760.18.

Below is the answer in the required JSON format.

--------------------------------------------------

{"solution": {"Taxes Payable Initial Value": "0.00", "Taxes Payable End Value": "42760.18"} }
